<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910913-0027</DOCNO><DOCID>910913-0027.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Sierra Pacific Resources:   Unit Wins Grant to Build   Cleaner-Burning Coal Plant</HL><DATE>09/13/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C6</SO><CO>   SRP</CO><MS>ENERGY (ENE)UTILITIES (UTI)</MS><IN>COAL PRODUCERS (COA)ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)</IN><GV>ENERGY DEPARTMENT (ERG)</GV><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEVADA (NV)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Sierra Pacific Resources said its unit, Sierra PacificPower Co., was awarded a federal grant to build a power plantusing cleaner burning fuel.   The Pinon Pine Power Project is expected to cost $160million in today's dollars, with one-half the money comingfrom the Department of Energy, the utility said. Thegovernment is also putting up half the $74 million whichutility officials said will be needed for operations andmaintenance during the plant's first four years of operation.Groundbreaking is set for 1993 with final completion by 1997.</LP><TEXT>   Sierra Pacific Power, based in Reno, Nev., was one of 31other companies that applied earlier this year for grantsfrom a $568 million pool of federal funds available from theDepartment of Energy's Clean Coal Technology program. ThePinon Pine project, an 80-watt plant to be built outside ofReno, is one of nine around the country selected to receivematching funds to demonstrate how to burn coal more cleanly.   The utility's stock rose 25 cents to $23 in late New YorkStock Exchange Composite trading yesterday.</TEXT></DOC>